{{Infobox scientist |name = Friedrich Leibniz |image = Friedrich Leibnütz.jpg |caption = |birth_date = 1597 |birth_place = [[Altenburg]] |death_date = 1652 |death_place = [[Leipzig]] |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = |field = [[Moral philosophy]] |work_institutions = [[University of Leipzig]] |alma_mater = [[University of Leipzig]] (M.A., 1622) |academic_advisors = |known_for = |prizes = |spouse = First unnamed wife, second unnamed wife, Catharina Schmuck |issue = [[Gottfried Leibniz]] |notable_students = [[Jakob Thomasius]] }} '''Friedrich Leibniz''' (or '''Leibnütz'''; 1597&ndash;1652)<ref name="Continuum "/> was a [[Lutheran]]<ref name="Continuum "/><ref>Brandon C. Look. (2007). [http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/leibniz/ Leibniz]. [[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]. Retrieved 2012-02-09 </ref> lawyer and a notary, registrar and professor of [[moral philosophy]] within [[Leipzig University]].<ref name="Continuum ">Brandon C. Look. {{cite book | url =https://books.google.com/?id=PTmmjB3nDyoC&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=Friedrich+Leibniz#v=onepage&q=Friedrich%20Leibniz&f=false | title = The Continuum Companion to Leibniz | publisher = - Continuum International Publishing Group, 2011 | isbn = 0826429750 | accessdate = 2012-01-26 | date = 2011-08-04 }}</ref><ref name="Houston">Gregory Brown (Professor at [[University of Houston]]). {{cite book | url =http://www.gwleibniz.com/friedrich_leibniz/friedrich_leibniz.html | title = Friedrich Leibniz | publisher = Leibniz Society of North America | accessdate = 2012-01-26 }}</ref><ref>See references of Heinrich Schepers and Ronald Calinger; in [[Richard S. Westfall]], [http://galileo.rice.edu/Catalog/NewFiles/leibniz.html ''The Galileo Project''], [[Rice University]]. Retrieved 2012-01-27. </ref><ref name="Jolley">Ariew, Roger. ''G. W. Leibniz, life and works.'' [http://cco.cambridge.org/extract?id=ccol0521365880_CCOL0521365880A003 Cambridge Collections Online]. In: Nicholas Jolley, {{cite book | url =https://books.google.com/?id=SnRis5Gdi8gC&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=friedrich+leibniz#v=onepage&q=friedrich%20leibniz&f=false | title = The Cambridge companion to Leibniz | doi=10.1017/CCOL0521365880.002 | publisher = Cambridge University Press, 1995| isbn = 0-521-36769-7 | accessdate = 2012-01-26 | year = 1995 }}</ref> He was the father of [[Gottfried Leibniz]].
==Biography== Leibniz was born in [[Altenburg]], the son of Ambrosious Leibniz, a civil servant, and a [[Leipzig]] noblewoman named Anna Deuerlin.<ref name="Houston"/>
He completed his [[master's degree]] at the University of Leipzig during 1622 and became an [[actuary]] in administration at the University.<ref name="Continuum "/> His first marriage in 1625 produced a son, Johann Friedrich, and a daughter, Anna Rosina. He was elected to the chair in moral philosophy at Leipzig in 1640. A childless marriage to a second wife ended with her death 1643.<ref name="Houston"/><ref name="genealogy.math.ndsu">Mitchel T. Keller ''et al''. [[North Dakota State University]]. {{cite book | url =http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=143630 | title = 58108-6050 | accessdate = 2012-01-26 }}</ref> A subsequent 1644 marriage to Catharina Schmuck, a daughter of a well known lawyer (or professor of law<ref name="Jolley" />) produced a son, the [[polymath]] [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]].<ref name="Houston"/>
{{cquote|On Sunday 21 June <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[New Style|NS]]: 1 July] 1646, my son Gottfried Wilhelm is born into the world a quarter after six in the evening, in Aquarius.<ref>It is possible that the words "in Aquarius" refer to the Moon &ndash; the Sun in Cancer; Sagittarius rising (Ascendant). See [http://www.astro.com/cgi/chart.cgi?wgid=wgeJw9js0KwjAQhJ9GUFilG2z9CXsOiHfPKYlpsIklTSnp07tFkTkMzLfszOxfnoR0gTTKaOhufRv9Auqd8zN5ayAAwgmwOTaA5yvWEFBYUYGbeqiA74fFO1A2BR0LfFmNES8wMWdJbdqog6X_z42ofj0rMzpbQs5uU1_Y1iq2rUvWHXayzWXghSF3pPMsu7HQHmUaCR_qAw0rOyM Astro-Databank chart of Gottfried Leibniz]. </ref><ref>The original has "1/4 uff 7 uhr" but there is no reason to assume that in the 17th century this meant a quarter ''to'' seven. The quote is given by Hartmut Hecht in ''Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz'' (Teubner-Archiv zur Mathematik Volume 2, 1992), in the first lines of chapter 2, ''Der junge Leibniz'', p. 15; see [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007%2F978-3-663-05995-0_2#page-1 H. Hecht, ''Der junge Leibniz'']; see also [https://play.google.com/books/reader?printsec=frontcover&output=reader&id=fHJMAAAAcAAJ&pg=GBS.RA1-PA3 G. E. Guhrauer, ''G. W. Frhr. v. Leibnitz''. B. 1. Breslau 1846, Anm. S. 4].</ref> }}
During 1646 Leibniz was vice chairman of the faculty of philosophy and also was Professor of Moral Philosophy at the University of Leipzig, in addition to employment as actuary.<ref name="Houston"/> He possessed a collection of books of ancient source.<ref name="Jolley"/> He died in [[Leipzig]].
{{cquote|... a competent though not original scholar, who devoted his time to his offices and to his family as a pious, Christian father.<ref>E. J. Aiton, ''Leibniz : A biography'' (Bristol- Boston, 1984). In: [http://www.gap-system.org/~history/Biographies/Leibniz.html MacTutor History of Mathematics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928090405/http://www.gap-system.org/~history/Biographies/Leibniz.html |date=2006-09-28 }}, by J O'Connor and E F Robertson, [[University of St Andrews]]. Retrieved 2012-01-26</ref> }}
Leibniz is notable because his mathematical "descendants," which include [[Carl Friedrich Gauss]], number more than 119,000.<ref>[http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=143630 Mathematics Genealogy Project entry for Friedrich Leibniz]</ref>
