[[File:Laika ac Juche Tower (12107747863).jpg|thumb|The [[Juche Tower|''Juche'' Tower]] and ''On the Juche Idea'' were both introduced for the 70th [[Day of the Sun|birth anniversary of Kim Il-sung]], whose ''[[Juche]]'' philosophy from thereon was exclusively interpreted by [[Kim Jong-il]].]] '''''On the Juche Idea: Treatise Sent to the National Seminar on the Juche Idea Held to Mark the 70th Birthday of the Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung, 31 March 1982''''' ({{Korean|hangul=주체 사상 에 대하여|mr=Chuch'e sasang e taehayŏ|context=north}}) is a treatise attributed to [[North Korean leader]] [[Kim Jong-il]] on the [[North Korea]]n ''[[Juche]]'' ideology. It is considered the most authoritative work on ''Juche''.
The work, although probably ghostwritten for him,<ref name="Myers2015"/> legitimized Kim as the sole ''bona fide'' interpreter of the ideology. The treatise systemizes Kim Jong-il and his father [[Kim Il-sung]]'s thought on the ''Juche'' philosophy. The treatise marks ''Juche''{{'}}s departure from the [[Dialectical materialism|materialism]] of [[Marxism–Leninism]] and posits the [[Class consciousness|consciousness of the massess]] as dependent on the working class leader.
According to Kim Jong-il, the ''Juche'' idea is composed of a philosophical principle, socio-historical principles, and guiding principles. The philosophical principle can be summarized with Kim Il-sung's maxim that "man is the master of everything and decides everything."{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}} The socio-historical principles entail that the working masses are the subject of history. The guiding principles are: independent stance, creative method, and giving precedence to ideological consciousness. Emphasis on independence in particular has given raise to Kim's ''[[Songun]]'', or military first, politics.
== Background == ''On the Juche Idea'' is one of Kim Jong-il's major writings on ''Juche''<ref name="DavidWest2011" /> and considered the most authoritative work on it.{{sfn|Kwak|Joo|2009|p=19}} It is a standard textbook on the subject.<ref name="jsto_Nort1">{{cite journal| title = North Korea in 1982: Continuing Revolution under Kim Jong Il| author = Rinn-Sup Shinn | date = 1983 | doi = 10.2307/2644331 | journal=Asian Survey|volume=23|number=1|page = 103 }}</ref> The treatise is a systematization of both [[President of North Korea|President]] [[Kim Il-sung]] and Kim Jong-il's thought on ''Juche'' philosophy{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}}{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=301}} and offers the most comprehensive account of ''Juche''.{{sfn|Kwak|Joo|2009|p=19}} Kim Il-sung's thought in particular began to be formulated as an original philosophy from the 1970s onward.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}} ''On the Juche Idea'' was sent to the national seminar on the ''Juche'' idea<ref name="DavidWest2011">{{cite journal|last=David-West|first=Alzo|date=January 2011|title=Between Confucianism and Marxism-Leninism: Juche and the Case of Chŏng Tasan|journal=Korean Studies|volume=35|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/74541165/between-confucianism-marxism-leninism-juche-case-ch-ng-tasan|page=105|doi=10.1353/ks.2011.0007}}</ref> on 31 March 1982 held on the occasion of the 70th [[Day of the Sun|birth anniversary of Kim Il-sung]] (15 April).{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}} The occasion was also honored with the unveiling of the [[Juche Tower|''Juche'' Tower]] in [[Pyongyang]].<ref name="RandallRandall2004">{{cite book|editor-first=Annie J.|editor-last=Randall|title=Music, Power, and Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aLqTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA113|date=22 December 2004|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-1-135-94691-3|pages=113, 116–117}}</ref>
In the treatise, Kim Jong-il links the birth of the ''Juche'' idea to Kim Il-sung's personal history as a guerrilla fighter during the [[anti-Japanese struggle]].<ref name="scho_Lee:">{{cite journal| title = The Political Philosophy of Juche| last= Lee | first=Grace |journal=Stanford Journal of East Asian Affairs | volume=3|number=1|date = 2003 | accessdate = 11 September 2015 | url = https://web.stanford.edu/group/sjeaa/journal3/korea1.pdf| page = 109 }}</ref> ''On the Juche Idea'' thus furthered [[Kim Il-sung's cult of personality]].{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=302}} Publishing the treatise helped Kim Jong-il to gain legitimacy,<ref name="jsto_Nort2">{{cite journal| title = North Korea in 1983: Transforming 'The Hermit Kingdom'?| author = Young Whan Kihl | date = 1984 | doi=10.2307/2644170|journal=Asian Survey|volume=24|number=1|page=101}}</ref> particularly emphasizing his intellectual prowess.<ref name="Mathesius2011">{{Cite web | title = Kim Jong-un's Catchphrase? | last = Mathesius | first = Konrad | work = NK News| date = 7 June 2011 | accessdate = 3 August 2016 | url = https://www.nknews.org/2011/06/kim-jong-uns-catchphrase/}}</ref> At the time of writing Kim Jong-il was working as the ideological chief of the country on behalf of his father.<ref name="dbc._Doln">{{cite web | title = Dolnośląska Digital Library – North Korea and its special economic zones: Re-establishing networks with the world economy? Prace Naukowe Uniwersytetu Ekonomicznego we Wrocławiu = Research Papers of Wrocław University of Economics, 2013, Nr 295, s. 93–108 | author = PSNC | last2 = Supercomputer | first2 = Poznan | last3 = Center | first3 = Networking | work = dbc.wroc.pl | date = | accessdate = 14 September 2015 | url = http://www.dbc.wroc.pl/dlibra/docmetadata?id=28804&from=publication | page=101}}</ref> Although it was probably ghostwritten for him,<ref name="Myers2015">{{cite book|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=North Korea's Juche Myth|date=1 October 2015|publisher=Sthele Press|location=Busan|isbn=978-1-5087-9993-1|page=162}}</ref> by being named as the author Kim Jong-il became the "one and only bona fide interpreter of the 'immortal Juche idea' of Kim Il Sung."{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=301}}
== Content == {{quote box| align = right| width = 25em|quote=In his early years of revolutionary activities, the leader {{bracket|[[Kim Il-sung]]}} was well versed in Marxism-Leninism. But he did not confine himself to applying Marxism-Leninism to the Korean revolution but pioneered a new phase of revolutionary theory from a steadfast Juche-based standpoint and resolved the problems arising in the revolutionary practice from a unique angle.|source=''On the Juche Idea''<ref>{{cite book|author=Kim Jong-il|title=On the Juche Idea : Treatise Sent to the National Seminar on the Juche Idea Held to Mark the 70th Birthday of the Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung March 31, 1982|url=http://www.korean-books.com.kp/en/packages/xnps/download.pg.php?306#.pdf|year=1982|location=[Pyongyang]|publisher=[Foreign Languages Publishing House]|oclc=9475822|page=7|access-date=13 October 2017}}</ref>| salign = right}} Kim Jong-il explains that ''Juche'' is a departure from [[Marxism–Leninism]] rather than simply a reinterpretation of it. According to Kim, ''Juche'' offers not only an "independent and creative" direction to the Korean revolution, but also establishes a new era for human history.{{sfn|Kwak|Joo|2009|p=19}} It is [[idealist]] as opposed to the [[Dialectical materialism|materialism]] of [[Marxism]].{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=216}} The work is considered somewhat abstract in style.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=217}}
In comparison to Kim Il-sung's writings, Kim Jong-il pays particular attention to [[Class consciousness|consciousness]] and the concept of the leader. These two are often linked.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=216}} According to [[Charles K. Armstrong]], the main message of the treatise is that "regardless of material circumstances, the masses owe unquestioning obedience to the Great Leader, who alone can bring the masses to consciousness", adding that the "message would be extremely useful for the North Korean state in the difficult years ahead", referring to the [[death of Kim Il-sung]] and the [[North Korean famine]] in the 1990s, soon after the publication of ''On the Juche Idea''.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=217}}
In ''On the Juche Idea'', Kim Jong-il divides ''Juche'' into three components: the philosophical principle, the socio-historical principles, and the guiding principles of the ''Juche'' idea.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}}
=== Philosophical principle === The philosophical principle entails that ''Juche'' is a [[Anthropocentrism|man-centered]] philosophy. Man has independence, {{Interlanguage link multi|Creativity (Juche)|ko|3=창조성 (주체사상)|lt=creativity}} and {{Interlanguage link multi|Consciousness (Juche)|ko|3=의식성 (주체사상)|lt=consciousness}}, which places man at the center of the world. This is described by the maxim coined by Kim Il-sung in a 1972 interview with Japanese journalists: "man is the master of everything and decides everything."{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}} Man transforms the world{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=301}} and embodies ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Chajusŏng|ko|3=자주성 (주체사상)}}'', or independence and autonomy.{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=302}} By putting man at the center, Kim Jong-il denies the existence of any supernatural power, although the ''Juche'' philosophy itself can be said to have [[Political religion|quasi-religious]] elements.{{sfn|Hale|2002|p=301}}
=== Socio-historical principles === The socio-historical principles of ''Juche'' can be summarized as follows: the working masses are the subject of history.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=386}} Human history is the struggle of the masses to realize their independence and defend it. Man's socio-historical mission is to transform both nature and society.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=387}} Here Kim departs from [[Marxism–Leninism]] by primarily setting man against nature rather than the [[proletariat]] against the [[bourgeois]] class.{{sfn|Kwak|Joo|2009|p=20}}
=== Guiding principles === There are three guiding principles in ''Juche'': #First, ''independent stance'' means ''Juche'' in ideology, independence in politics, [[Autarky|self-sufficiency in economy]] and self-reliance in defence.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=387}} These four aspects of the independent stance can be already found in Kim Il-sung's 1965 speech given in [[Indonesia]], ''[[On Socialist Construction and the South Korean Revolution in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]''.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=216}} Even though ''On the Juche Idea'' mentions economy, it is not given precedence. Words like "development" and "growth" are more often used to refer to ideology rather than economy.<ref name="Kivimäki2014">{{cite book|last=Kivimäki|first=Timo|title=The Long Peace of East Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ssmaBAAAQBAJ&pg=PR4|date=28 May 2014|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|location=Farnham|isbn=978-1-4724-2229-3|page=89}}</ref> However, noting that an economy built on "self-reliance does not mean building an economy in isolation", Kim does hint at limited economic reforms. Sure enough, a law on joint-ventures was passed in 1984.<ref name="dbc._Doln" /> #The second principle, ''creative method'', means that all problems arising in the revolution and construction are to be solved by relying on the creativity of the masses.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=387}} #The third and final guiding principle is giving ''precedence to ideological consciousness'' over all other work.{{sfn|Kim|2001|p=387}}
== Legacy == ''On the Juche Idea'' has been since used as a justification for Kim Jong-il's ''[[Songun]]'', or army-first, politics. The justification can be found in an aspect of one of the guiding principles of ''Juche'', which Kim has "elevated": self-reliance in defence.{{sfn|Kwak|Joo|2009|p=35}} Kim went on to publish "The Workers' Party of Korea Is a ''Juche''-type Revolutionary Party which Inherited the Glorious Tradition of the DIU" in October 1982 and focusing in it more on Kim Il-sung's guerrilla activities.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=217}}
