[[File:Agust h bjarnason professor.jpg|thumb|200px]]
'''Ágúst H. Bjarnason''' (20 August 1875 – 22 September 1952) was  the son of [[Hákon Bjarnason]], and [[Jóhanna K. Þorleifsdóttir]]. Ágúst was a pioneer in teaching psychology in Iceland and the first one to write books on [[psychology]] in Icelandic.{{citeneeded|date=January 2016}}

A revolution begin in Icelandic psychological history when Ágúst and [[Guðmundur Finnbogason]] went to study psychology and [[philosophy]] at [[University of Copenhagen]]. They both finished master's degrees in 1901 and then doctorals in 1911. They both had psychology as majors. The mentor of Ágúst (and Guðmundur) was [[Harald Høffding]]. Ágúst's doctoral dissertation was about the French philosopher [[Jean-Marie Guyau]].{{citeneeded|date=January 2016}}

He was a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]], describing himself as Iceland's "only card-carrying Unitarian."<ref name="Jr.Gissurarson1997">{{cite book|author1=William H. Swatos, Jr.|author2=Loftur Reimar Gissurarson|title=Icelandic Spiritualism: Mediumship and Modernity in Iceland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLk0gqFi_1EC&pg=PA62|date=1 January 1997|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-2577-1|pages=62}}</ref>

